# Loneliness, Half Truths, and the Entrepreneurial Life

“It’s lonely at the top,” they say.

It’s easy to believe when you’ve got a tax bill hanging over your head, a dishonest employee embezzling money from your business, a partner taking an unfair share of your business, or an angry customer cussing you out.

However, it’s half a truth and half a lie.

**The Truth: You will always face different challenges than 90% of the world.**

Although sources vary, only 1 out of 10 people own their own business. This means that by definition, you face different challenges than 90% of the world. Eliminate solopreneurs and contract workers, and the percentage increases considerably.

Without diving into a math lesson, the 80/20 principle says that the larger your organization, the more unique the challenges you face. A simple look within your organization will quickly tell you this:

* In a 5-person organization, you face challenges that 80% of your team won’t face.  
* In a 10-person organization, you face challenges that 90% of your team won’t face.  
* In a 20-person organization, you face challenges that 95% of your team won’t face.  
* In a 50-person organization, you face challenges that 98% of your team won’t face.

The bigger your organization, the less likely are are to find someone who can identify with the challenges you face. For business owners who never make new friends as they grow, it’s understandable that they conclude that it is “lonely at the top”.

However, it’s a lie to say it’s inevitable.

**The Lie: I can’t be friends with the rest of the world.**

Despite the vast differences, it’s not only possible to be friends with the rest of the world. It’s crucial that you are.

Your ability to connect with people different than yourself is an essential skill of leadership and business. As long as you stay locked in your own world, believing that no one else can identify or relate with you, you will limit your ability to lead and influence others.

Just as important, it will limit your effectiveness. Your inspiration will always come from outside your normal circles. Intentional friendships with people different from yourself will broaden your perspective of life and open you up to new ideas.

**The Lie: I can’t find people who face the same challenges that I do.**

While most of the world won’t relate to your challenges, it’s important you surround yourself with people who do relate. Your greatest growth will come when you surround yourself with people who believe in you, support you, and offer you time-tested insights and resources.

This is more than just a fireside *Kumbayah* or just getting together to shoot the breeze. This means finding others who will intentionally challenge you and help you to grow. It requires that you intentionally spend time with people who are leading organizations bigger than you, whether in your own industry or outside.

This simple act will not only give you better ideas, it will give you greater accountability to act on the ideas you know you must execute.
